## Part VII: AI and the Final Convergence

What comes next is not a departure from the preceding argument. It is its logical conclusion.

Artificial intelligence systems — specifically the large language models that have become, since 2022, a daily presence in the intellectual lives of hundreds of millions of people — are the most sophisticated manifestation yet of the data-language complex. They are trained on the accumulated written output of human civilization, which means they encode, with extraordinary fidelity, the dominant linguistic registers, epistemic conventions, and cultural assumptions of the societies whose writing is overrepresented in their training data. They then reproduce those conventions at scale, in response to the queries of users who may not recognize the epistemological commitments embedded in the form of the response itself.

This is the point your friend who wrote her thesis on texting and language understood, and that most public discourse about AI has not yet caught up to. The question is not merely whether AI produces factually accurate outputs. It is whether AI, deployed at sufficient scale and intimacy, begins to reshape the cognitive substrate of the people who use it — not through deliberate manipulation but through the same mechanism that text messaging reshaped the register of casual written English, that Google reshaped the relationship between knowledge and retrieval, that algorithmic feeds reshaped the capacity for sustained attention.

Recent research has documented what some are calling the “data coil” problem: AI models are trained on human-generated text; once deployed, they influence the text that humans generate; that influenced text then enters the training data for subsequent models. The circle closes. The linguistic and epistemic conventions of AI begin to colonize the human-generated text that will train the next generation of AI, which will further influence the humans generating the text after that. The feedback loop is already running. Its long-term effects on the diversity of thought, the range of available linguistic registers, and the cognitive independence of people who spend significant portions of their intellectual lives inside AI-mediated information environments remain, for now, unmeasured — but not unmeasurable.

The concern, articulated in the emerging research literature on AI’s epistemic effects, is not that AI makes people stupid. It is that AI, by providing fluent, confident, authoritative-sounding responses to almost any question, reduces the experiential frequency of the cognitive states most associated with genuine inquiry: uncertainty, productive confusion, the effortful construction of understanding from resistant material. When Stanovich’s framework of cognition distinguishes between autonomous (instinctive), algorithmic (computational), and reflective (rationally self-regulating) levels of thinking, the concern about AI is precisely that it offloads what should be reflective work onto algorithmic processing — and that over time, as with GPS and spatial memory, the reflective capacity that is not exercised begins to atrophy.

The AI vernacular — its characteristic rhythm of qualified assertion, its hedged multiperspectivalism, its preference for the tidy synthesis over the generative contradiction — is already bleeding into how educated, digitally native people write emails, frame arguments, and structure their own thinking. This is not surprising. Every dominant medium has done this. What is new is the speed, the intimacy, and the fact that this particular medium is explicitly modeled on the appearance of authoritative human thought. It is not a neutral transmission channel. It is a highly persuasive simulation of the kind of thinking that produces knowledge — which, in sufficient doses and without sufficient critical resistance, may gradually substitute for it.

